Experiment No.—6: Node-RED for IoT Dashboard 

a) Install and configure Node-RED on Raspberry Pi 
b) Create a flow to turn LED ON/OFF via browser 
c) Add visual interface for sensor data (e.g., temperature)

Steps, Code & Output: 

(a) Install and Configure Node-RED on Raspberry Pi 
Steps 

1. Open the Terminal on Raspberry Pi. 

2. Install Node-RED using the following command: 
bash <(curl -sL https://raw.githubusercontent.com/node-red/linux
installers/master/deb/update-nodejs-and-nodered) 

3. Enable Node-RED to start automatically at boot: 
sudo systemctl enable nodered.service 

4. Start Node-RED service:
node-red-start 

5. Open a web browser and access the Node-RED editor: 
http://localhost:1880

Output 
• Node-RED starts successfully in the terminal. 
• The Node-RED editor interface opens in the browser showing: 
  o Node palette 
  o Flow workspace 
  o Deploy button 

(b) Create a Flow to Turn LED ON/OFF via Browser 
Connection

Component     Raspberry Pi 
LED Anode     GPIO17 
LED Cathode   GND 

Steps 
1. Open the Node-RED editor in the browser. 

2. Install node-red-dashboard from Manage Palette. 

3. Drag the following nodes into the workspace: 
  o Dashboard Button Node 
  o Raspberry Pi GPIO Output Node 

4. Configure the GPIO Output node: 
  o Pin → GPIO17 

5. Connect nodes as: 
Dashboard Button → GPIO Output Node → LED 

6. Configure button payload values: 
  o 1 → LED ON 
  o 0 → LED OFF 

7. Click Deploy.

Flow Logic 

Browser Dashboard Button 
↓ 
Send Payload (1 or 0) 
↓ 
GPIO Output Node 
↓ 
LED ON/OFF 


Output 

Open the dashboard: 
http://localhost:1880/ui 

  • Press ON button → LED turns ON 
  • Press OFF button → LED turns OFF 

This confirms that the LED can be controlled remotely using a browser-based dashboard.


(c) Add Visual Interface for Sensor Data (Temperature and Humidity) 

Sensor Used 

DHT11 Temperature and Humidity Sensor 

Connection 

DHT11 Pin     Raspberry Pi 
VCC           3.3V 
DATA           GPIO4
GND           GND


Steps 
1. Open the Node-RED editor: 
http://localhost:1880 

2. Install required nodes from Manage Palette: 
  o node-red-dashboard 
  o node-red-contrib-dht-sensor 

3. Drag the following nodes into the workspace: 
  o Inject Node 
  o DHT Sensor Node 
  o Dashboard Gauge Node 
  o Dashboard Text Node 

4. Configure the DHT Sensor Node: 
  o Sensor type → DHT11 
  o GPIO pin → GPIO4 

5. Connect nodes as: 
Inject Node → DHT Sensor Node → Dashboard Gauge / Text 

6. Click Deploy.

Flow Logic 

Inject Node 
↓ 
DHT11 Sensor Node 
↓ 
Dashboard Gauge / Text 
↓ 
Display Temperature & Humidity 

Output 

Open the dashboard: 

http://localhost:1880/ui 

Example display:

Parameter       Value 
Temperature    26 °C 
Humidity       58 % 

• The dashboard shows real-time temperature and humidity values. 
• Data updates whenever the sensor reading is triggered.
